lly started in Vila do Conde, thus we were sailing with sailing with the currents back to USG (Corpus Christi). Obviously higher bunker consumption in port due the long port stay in VDC. Lastly, the bunker hedge. We are unhedged on one of the three liftings and we decided to move the second hedge for the third and final lift since the hedge has a November settlement date \u2013 so we \u201Clost\u201D 100k which was the estimated hedge revenue. As mentioned in the fixture note we bunkered at a layberth in Corpus Christi, adding 30k to the usual port cost. We explored the option to bunker at Bolivar Roads, but that would have resulted in the vessel being late for the laycan. 9.82 days longer voyage, 9.16 of which on demurrage at $ 18,750 \u2013 adds 170k in revenue."},{"modifiedDate":"2022-07-19T18:45:43.52","modifiedByFull":"Rauston, Gustav","remark":"Bunker hedge allocated to the third and final lifting"},{"modifiedDate":"2022-07-05T13:13:54.867","modifiedByFull":"Rauston, Gustav","remark":"Estimated demurrage income increase TCE considerably"},{"modifiedDate":"2022-06-28T16:28:54.66","modifiedByFull":"Rauston, Gustav","remark":"Lower than expected bunker consumption southbound when applying latest noon report"}],"offhireList":[],"tcNumber":null,"tcOutIdEncrypted":null,"tcReletDetail":null}